  "biography_html": "<div class=\"research-section\">\n<p class=\"research-text\">Theopompus of Chios was a Greek historian and rhetorician of the 4th century BCE. Born around 378 BCE on Chios, he was exiled due to his father&#x27;s pro-Spartan stance and studied in Athens under the orator Isocrates. Recalled to Chios by Alexander the Great around 333 BCE, he was exiled again after Alexander&#x27;s death and spent his final years in Egypt at the court of Ptolemy I, dying after 320 BCE.</p>\n<p class=\"research-text\">Ancient critics like Dionysius of Halicarnassus describe him as a moralizing, digressive, and sharply critical writer. His major works, surviving only in fragments, are historical. These include the Hellenica, a 12-book continuation of Thucydides covering the years 411 to 394 BCE, and the Philippica, a monumental 58-book history centered on Philip II of Macedon that included wide-ranging ethnographic digressions. He also composed rhetorical works, now lost, such as an Epitome of Herodotus.</p>\n<p class=\"research-text\">Theopompus was a major historian, considered with Ephorus as one of Isocrates&#x27; two great pupils. His Philippica was ambitious in scope, framing Macedonian ascendancy within a broad geographical context. His method—combining extensive research with a strong, judgmental authorial voice—represents a significant development in Greek historiography between Thucydides and the Hellenistic era.</p>\n</div>",
